<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18480228-969">
               <interp inst="t18480228-969" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18480228"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18480228-969" type="date" value="18480228"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18480228-969-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-969-18480228 t18480228-969-offence-1 t18480228-969-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>969. <persName id="def1-969-18480228" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-969-18480228" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-969-18480228" type="surname" value="PETTIT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-969-18480228" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM PETTIT</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18480228-969-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18480228-969-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18480228-969-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>, feloniously receiving 421<hi rend="italic">lbs.</hi> weight of wool value 16<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; and two woollen bags, 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18480228-name-1259" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1259" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1259" type="surname" value="DALBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1259" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18480228-969-offence-1 t18480228-name-1259"></join>Thomas Dalby</persName>. (See page 683.)</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1260" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1260" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1260" type="surname" value="DALBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1260" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS DALBY.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a wool-dealer, in Marlborough-place, Kent-road—I have a warehouse in Grange-walk, Bermondsey—I saw a man named Verrall tried here last Session. On 24th Dec. I received information, went to my warehouse, and missed two bags of wool—I had not sold them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When was your warehouse closed? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Generally about six o'clock—it was closed that night by a woman, who</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184802280183"></xptr>
               <p>is here—she had the keys—there was only one man there, who had the care of the horses—I have been to Mr. Broad's to make inquiries—I saw some wool there of the same kind as that I had lost, but I would not swear to it—it was finely combed wool—I know Mr. Broad to be a very respectable man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1261" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1261" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1261" type="surname" value="DALBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1261" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DALBY.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the nephew of Mr. Thomas Dalby. On 23rd Dec. I left his warehouse a little before six o'clock—I last saw the two bags of wool safe about four—I went next morning about nine o'clock, and the bags were gone—I saw an impression on some manure there, as if the bags had been on it—they would not have occasion to be put on it in the ordinary course of business.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1262" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1262" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1262" type="surname" value="M'DONALD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1262" type="given" value="ELIEA"></interp>ELIEA M'DONALD.</persName>
                  </hi> I left the premises safe on Thursday night, 23rd Dec., next morning I found them all locked, as I had left them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1263" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1263" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1263" type="surname" value="DALBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1263" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DALBY</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> Can you state how a person could get in? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Over the gates outside, and by opening a trap-door—supporting that to be done, the manure was in such a position that the wool would be thrown upon it, and there were some locks of wool on the manure—a person might have got in at the scutch-door without breaking at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1264" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1264" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1264" type="surname" value="SWAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1264" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM SWAN.</persName>
                  </hi> I live with my father, a butcher, in Grange-road. Between seven and eight o'clock in the evening, on 23rd Dec., I was passing from Grange-road into Grange-walk—I saw Carney's horse and cart standing under Mr. Dalby's scutch-loft door—I knew Carney before—he was in the cart—directly the cart was backed up, the door was opened, and one bag was thrown down—it nearly went on Carney, and before he moved that one the other was sent down—I saw some persons in the loft, but I could not see who they were—I should say there must have been more than one, as the bags were thrown out so quick—Carney set the bags to rights and went away—I went and told my father.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1265" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1265" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1265" type="surname" value="CARNEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1265" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS CARNEY.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the brother of the man who was tried here last Sessions. On the Wednesday before Christmas, Verrall came to my mother's house—I did not know him, only by seeing him about the street—I did not know his name before—he used often to come to my mother's house for the horse and cart—I knew he was in Mr. Pettit's employ—mu brother was out at the time, delivering coke, and Verrall said he would call up again when he was ready—he said he wanted my brother to move some hurdles and things—he said his master sent him up for the cart—I told him I would send my brother down—Verrall went aways, and I did not see him again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1266" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1266" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1266" type="surname" value="BARRETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1266" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BARRETT.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a coal-whipper—I am brother-in-law of Carney, who was tried here last Sessions. On the night of the 23rd Dec. I was at Carney's house, when Verrall came—I heard him say his master had sent him up for Carney to do a job for him—Carney said he would go, as he was ready—he went about seven o'clock, with his horse and cart—that place is about a quarter of a mile from where the wool was taken—next morning I was riding with Carney, and he got out and went into a yard in Russell-street—I saw the prisoner come down from the yard—he took Carney into a public-house, and paid him some money, and <hi rend="italic">stood</hi> a pot of beer while he was paying him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had you even seen the prisoner before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—this was on the Thursday before Christmas, about twelve or one o'clock in the day, at the Rose public-house—I was in the cart, and they called me to have a glass of beer—a young woman served us—I think I should know her if I saw her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1267" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1267" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1267" type="surname" value="EDWARDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1267" type="given" value="GEORGE MILLS"></interp>GEORGE MILLS EDWARDS.</persName>
                  </hi> I live at Woolwich. On the 23rd Dec. I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184802280184"></xptr>
               <p>lived as servant at Mr. Pool's, the Rose, in Russell-street, Bermondsey, Between seven and eight on that evening I saw Thomas Carney, with his cart, go up the turning alongside the Rose public-house, and draw up to Mr. Pettit's gateway, and I saw no more of him—I saw Verrall at the bottom of the yard—I had been in the yard about three minutes before—there were two bags of wool in the cart—next morning I saw the prisoner standing against his own gate, and there was a cart with a bag of wool in it, similar to what I had seen in Carney's cart the night before—I went to Mr. Wood's about my business, and when I came back the cart was gone—I saw the pri<lb></lb>soner again that day, in front of the Rose public-house, with Carney and his brother-in law—they had a pot of beer, and I saw some money pass from the prisoner, but I cannot tell what.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You were examined before, and the Jury disbelieved you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> "I do not know, they acquitted the two prisoners—I am not doing anything now—I left Mr. Pool's in Jan.—I left on my own account, without giving notice—I went away in the evening, and did not go back—I went after my character—I lived with Mr. Pool from July last, and I lived before that with Mr. Buckeridge, a publican, for six months—I was not brought up to any profession—I have been to sea—I was never engaged in any smug<lb></lb>gling transaction—I lad off Deal for a week—I was assistant-steward of a convict ship for two years—I did not <hi rend="italic">run</hi> any goods at Deal—I and my uncle have not been engaged in smuggling—before I was lying off Deal, I had been lying at Deptford and Woolwich, taking in prisoners—I now have my victuals and my lodging at my mother's—I walk about in the day, look<lb></lb>ing after a situation—I have heard of a situation this morning, to as servant in an engineer's office—I have done nothing since Jan, last—I live with my mother, and have not been out of Woolwich further than to Plum<lb></lb>stead and London, backwards and forwards—when I come to London, my mother pays my passage—I have no other means of getthing money, without I earn it—mu mother is a laundress—my father is living in Woolwich—he is a baker my trade, but he is bedrideen.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You lived in one situation two years, in another eighteen months, and in the last from July? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; and before I went to sea I lived with Mr. Dell, a wine-merchant, four years—I have a written character from my last place (<hi rend="italic">producing it</hi>)—it was given me by Mr. Pool.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1268" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1268" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1268" type="surname" value="RADFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1268" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE RADFORD</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">police-sergeant, M 19.</hi>) I apprehended Carney, and began to look after the prisoner on 24th Dec., between nine and ten at night—I knew where he lived, but had not known him before—I was not able to find him at his premises—I made all the inquiries I could on the subject—I was not able to get him—I did not know Verrall before he was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> In the yard where the prisoner's premises are, are there not many people? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There are workshops and warehouses—the pri<lb></lb>soner put in bail last Saturday fortnight—I have been looking for him before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BROAD</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY.</hi> I know the prisoner—he is a fell<lb></lb>monger—I have purchased wool of him regularly two or three times a week—on 24th Dec. I purchased of him about a hundred weight super-head wool and about a hundred weight of Dutch—that was not the wool that Mr. Dalby looked at at my premises—he looked at some wool that came in three or four days afterwards from Mr. Pettit—what Mr. Dalby wanted to look at was combing wool—the other wool is short.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you dealt with the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I should say three or four months—I suppose when Mr. Dalby came, he came</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184802280185"></xptr>
               <p>for the purpose of seeing woll which had been stolen by Verrall and Carney, and had been sold to me by the prisoner—I was not there when he came—I heard he had come about some wool that the prisoner was supposed to have stolen—I know what wool Mr. Dalby saw, because I came in just as he went out—he saw the wool which the prisoner had delivered to me—it was lying out—it was called fine-combed wool—he said he could not swear to it—there was about 3 1/4 cwts. of it—I was not at home when it was brought, but I believe it was brought by Verrall and by Pettit's brother-in-law, on our track—I looked at it, and put a price upon it—I think I looked at it the day after it came, it was after Christmas—I believe it came in on a Monday—I did not look at it till Thursday or Friday—our foreman pointed it out to me—I know by the book when the wool came in—our foreman keeps the book—he is not here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18480228-969-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-969-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-969-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>.</hi>
               </p>
            </div1>
